 5$ rad\nover an $\\sim 81$ km separation (1.7 orbits) while typical neutron stars\nexhibit phase differences of $\\geq 20$ rad. Although a difference of $\\sim 5$\nrad can be measured by current gravitational wave laser interferometers (e.g.,\naLIGO/Virgo), uncertainties in the individual masses and spins will likely\nprevent distinguishing such compact, massive neutron stars from black holes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 15 Nov 2019 20:38:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 26 Feb 2020 20:40:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-02-28"}
